-- 
-- Wed Mar 26, 2014 10:07PM EDT
-- None



March 27 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  IMF RUSHES THROUGH $15 BLN UKRAINE BAILOUT (http://link.reuters.com/kyz87v)  BOFA IN $9.5 BLN SETTLEMENT WITH REGULATOR (http://link.reuters.com/vuz87v)  FED REJECTS CITI'S 2014 DIVIDEND AND STOCK BUYBACK PLANS (http://link.reuters.com/fyz87v)  MEXICO OPENS DEEP WATER OILFIELDS TO TENDER (http://link.reuters.com/gyz87v)  CANDY CRUSHED AS KING TAKES 15 PCT HIT (http://link.reuters.com/hyz87v)  Overview  Sources said the International Monetary Fund would announce a rescue package for Ukraine of about $15 billion as early as Thursday, hoping that the initial aid payments could be made by the end of April.  Bank of America <BAC.N> agreed on Wednesday to pay $9.5 billion to settle claims it sold U.S. housing regulators faulty mortgage bonds.  The U.S. Federal Reserve rejected the capital plans of five large banks including Citigroup <C.N> as part of its annual stress test, but cleared Bank of America <BAC.N> and Goldman Sachs <GS.N> after they agreed to lower buyback and dividend proposals.  Mexico expects to issue tenders for some deep water oilfields next year as it welcomes private investment at its oil and gas exploration and production sector.